 class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><strong>What Exercises Are Good to Do With a Bar Pad?</strong></h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338486" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338486"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf_gs-text-paragraph-1 gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>All exercises where you have to place a barbell on any part of your body (hips, back) and have it stay there throughout the entire movement are ones you can use a bar pad for. The list includes not only hip thrusts but also squats and lunges. Some gym goers think that using a pad is for “sissies”; however, if you get bruised easily or if you feel pain from the barbell when doing any of these exercises, it’s smarter to get a barbell pad and start training normally.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338324" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338324"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><strong>What Are the Benefits of Barbell Pads for Hip Thrusts?</strong></h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338491" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338491" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Many lifters don’t think they need a barbell hip thrust pad and either doesn’t use one at all or just end up rolling up yoga mats and gym towels as makeshift padding for hip thrusts.&nbsp;</p><p>Unfortunately, these smart and on-the-spot solutions are a lot less comfortable than an actual bar pad for hip thrusts simply because the comfort level and ease of use are not near the same level. Along with that, using slippery objects like yoga mats and towels can be unsafe and lead to slipping and falling.&nbsp;</p><p>With that said, getting a bar cushion for hip thrusts is not that expensive at all and is definitely worth the trouble if you plan on doing the movement regularly. However, that’s not the only reason why you should want to buy a barbell pad for hip thrusts, and below, we will see all the other benefits this piece of fitness equipment offers.&nbsp;</p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338489" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1700124338489"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;">They Prevent Bruises</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338492" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338492" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Doing hip thrusts without barbell cushions can not only be painful, but it can also cause some serious bruising, especially if you’re lifting heavy weights. This usually happens because the barbell tends to puts a ton of stress on your hip bones, and this ends up putting your tissue between two hard objects - the barbell and your bones. Of course, an exercise like the glute bridge pad is not needed as the weight is likely not to be heavy, and it won’t cause you any harm.</p><p>Now, many of you might be thinking that getting a bruise is not that big of a deal, and it’s not something worth worrying over. However, if you get a more serious bruise, it can actually hurt, and it will make it more difficult to you to do hip thrusts the next day and the day after.&nbsp;</p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338307" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1700124338307"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;">Versatility</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338494" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338494" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Although we’re discussing why a foam barbell pad is needed for hip thrusts, the reality is that one of the best things about this fitness accessory is the fact that you can use it for many exercises. The best example is for squats, as for some people carrying a barbell on their back and close to their neck can also lead to bruising and makes it more challenging for them to balance the weight of the barbell effectively.&nbsp;</p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338479" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1700124338479"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;">Make the Exercise Feel More Comfortable</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338493" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338493" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>The main idea behind using a barbell pad is to make the movement feel more comfortable while you’re training, especially if you’re doing heavy squats and hip thrusts. If you get a high-quality barbell pad, it will be made of a thick foam cushion that prevents direct contact between your skin and the barbell.&nbsp;</p><p>Why does comfort matter? Because when you feel more comfortable during the exercise, you can perform the movement with better form and control, which will ultimately make it easier for you to reach your lifting goals.&nbsp;</p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338490" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1700124338490"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><font color="#000000"><b>Less Direct Contact With the Gym Barbells</b></font></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338495" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338495" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>We all know that the equipment in the gym is not always the cleanest. And it’s something that you need to consider when touching all the barbells and machines there. What’s good about using a barbell pad is that it will help you avoid direct contact with the barbells in the gym, which will be crucial for hygienic reasons.&nbsp;</p><p>Along with that, while some gyms do offer a barbell pad, a ton of other people have likely used it before you, and it has absorbed all their sweat, which is something you might want to avoid getting in direct contact with.&nbsp;</p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1700124338501" class="gf_row gf_row-gap-0" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1700124338501" data-row-gap="0px" data-extraclass="" data-layout-lg="12" data-layout-md="12" data-layout-sm="12" data-layout-xs="12" style="display: block;"><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1658828961229" data-id="1658828961229"><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338497" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1700124338497" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/b64561d7-f66b-4f86-966e-29922b136a5b/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/best-barbell-pads.jpg" alt="best barbell pads" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1200" height="800" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338498" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338498"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Support During Hip Thrusts</h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338496" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338496" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><div>We already said that one of the main functions of the barbell hip thrust pad is offering you support while you perform the exercise. Similar to knee sleeves or wrist wraps, padding helps keep your body safe and enables you to lift more weight without fearing you will get bruised. Along with that, the fact that they make it more comfortable for you to lift heavy weights helps ensure you will maintain proper technique and form throughout the entire movement.&nbsp;</div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338504" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1700124338504"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;">When Do You Need Barbell Pads for Squats?</span></h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338503" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338503" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><div>If you feel any pressure on your upper back and neck while doing squats, it’s a good idea to get a pad. The main thing that the pad does is help ease the pressure that you put on your upper body when lifting heavy weights. The thick foam that a good pad is made from will help evenly distribute the weight of the barbell across your shoulders, upper back, and neck, making exercises like squats and lunges more comfortable to do.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>Along with that, if you tend to easily bruise and you see marks on your back after heavy lifting, you can prevent all that with a good barbell pad.&nbsp;</div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338502" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1700124338502"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><font color="#000000"><b>When Do You Need Barbell Pads for Hip Thrusts?</b></font></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338500" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338500"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf_gs-text-paragraph-1 gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>If you’re performing a real hip thrust with a barbell and not a glute bridge, you will need some padding. That’s because using the barbell can lead to bruises, and it can make the movement feel more uncomfortable and even painful, especially if you’re lifting a heavy weight. However, don’t assume you only need a barbell pad when and if you lift a ton of weight. In reality, for some people, even feeling the weight on the barbell squishing their tissue can be painful, and those that easily bruise also have to use a pad at all times. Otherwise, they risk feeling a ton of pain while performing this great exercise.</p></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338508" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338508" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338505" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1700124338505"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><font color="#000000"><b>What to Look For in Barbell Pads?</b></font></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338507" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338507"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf_gs-text-paragraph-1 gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>If you’re already convinced that you need to go and buy a barbell pad, then you need to consider some features that it needs to have so that it can be as useful to you as possible. Let’s take a look at what they are.&nbsp;</p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338499" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1700124338499"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;">Pad Material & Thickness</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338506" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338506"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf_gs-text-paragraph-1 gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Two things that you should always look into before deciding on a barbell pad are its thickness and the material it's made from. That’s because these two features are the most vital ones for the pad’s ability to withstand the pressure of a heavy barbell. In an ideal situation, you want the pad to be made of silky smooth, thick foam with an overall thickness that can be between 3 to 2.1 inches. Along with the thick foam or rubber that will ensure comfort, you also need a cover on top of them that is anti-slip and won’t absorb moisture. The combination of those 3 things can be difficult to find, but it’s best if you want to buy a product that you will successfully use for a long time.&nbsp;</p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338515" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1700124338515"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;">Securing Mechanism</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338514" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338514"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf_gs-text-paragraph-1 gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>There are many ways to secure a pad to a barbell. And which one you choose depends more on the kind of weight you’re looking to lift rather than on the design. In case you don’t plan on lifting a ton of weight, you will want to consider a simpler design, such as the slip one - it’s easy to put on and take off, which makes it ideal for quick gym workouts.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1700124338519" class="gf_row gf_row-gap-0" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1700124338519" data-row-gap="0px" data-extraclass=""><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1686320640542" data-id="1686320640542"><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1700124338521" class="gf_row gf_row-gap-0" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1700124338521" data-layout-lg="6+6" data-extraclass="" data-layout-md="6+6" data-layout-sm="6+6" data-layout-xs="8+4" data-row-gap="0px"><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-6 gf_col-md-6 gf_col-sm-6 gf_col-xs-8" id="c-1686566620521" data-id="1686566620521"><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338512" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1700124338512"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><b>Tips From the Champ</b></h2></div></div></div><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-6 gf_col-md-6 gf_col-sm-6 gf_col-xs-4" id="c-1686566621695" data-id="1686566621695"><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338509" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1700124338509" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-right-lg gf-elm-right-md gf-elm-right-sm gf-elm-right-xs" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/d583efb1-a2f6-4d53-8a26-d6ddafaa60fd/7350738.png" alt="" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="512" height="512" data-width="50%" data-height="auto" title="" natural-width="512" natural-height="512"></div></div></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338522" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338522"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc="">if you’re doing hip thrusts regularly and with a ton of weight, you will want to consider buying a pad that has velcro straps attached to it, which helps with balance and security. With that said, if you truly plan on going hard and lifting close to a one-rep maximum often, then you should consider a pad with straps. While they do take longer to attach to the barbell, the straps remain the safest way to prevent the barbell from slipping and potentially causing injuries.&nbsp;</div></div><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1700124338517" class="gf_row gf_row-gap-0" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1700124338517" data-layout-lg="6+6" data-extraclass="" data-layout-md="6+6" data-layout-sm="6+6" data-layout-xs="12+12" data-row-gap="0px"><div class="gf_column gf_col-md-6 gf_col-sm-6 gf_col-lg-6 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1686564763470" data-id="1686564763470"><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338518" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1700124338518" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-exc=""><a href="https://torokhtiy.com/pages/oleksiy-torokhtiy" target="_blank"><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/fc0a1a19-2e31-4fa8-a43b-9c408a123923/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/Oleksiy.jpg" alt="" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="531" height="533" data-width="20%" data-height="auto" title="" natural-width="531" natural-height="533"></a></div></div></div><div class="gf_column gf_col-md-6 gf_col-sm-6 gf_col-lg-6 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1686564765807" data-id="1686564765807"><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338528" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338528"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf_gs-text-paragraph-1 gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p><b><a href="https://torokhtiy.com/pages/oleksiy-torokhtiy" class="" target="_blank">Oleksiy Torokhtiy</a></b></p></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338533" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338533"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf_gs-text-paragraph-1 gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p><span style="font-weight: 700;">Olympic Weightlifting&nbsp;</span><span style="font-weight: 700; color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: inherit; text-align: inherit; letter-spacing: 0px;">Champion</span></p></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338511" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1700124338511"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;">Ergonomic Design</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338530" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338530"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf_gs-text-paragraph-1 gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>You need an ergonomic design because it’s what will ensure that you feel comfortable with the barbell on your bones while performing the movement. The ideal barbell pad should have balanced thickness and length so that it neither feels too thin nor too bulky.&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p>Furthermore, you should look for a versatile barbell pad that works for all the exercises we discussed - not only hip thrusts but also squats, lunges, front squats, and others. That, however, means that it should keep your body’s contours in mind through the different movements. Typically, barbells have a groove in the middle that enables them to be placed comfortably close to your neck when doing lunges and squats - that’s the exact place where the thickest part of the pad should be.&nbsp;</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338526" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1700124338526" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/2a569448-b1ae-4814-a924-b0d6e007bcfc/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/Barbell%20Pads.png" alt="Barbell Pads" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1920" height="1280" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="" natural-width="1920" natural-height="1280"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338513" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1700124338513"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;">Slip Resistance</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338535" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338535"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf_gs-text-paragraph-1 gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>If you have any experience with lifting, you know that when you get past the warm-up sets, your body will start to get a little sweaty. Unfortunately, loaded barbells can also become a bit slippery, and that combination can potentially lead to injuries if the heavyweight slips and falls off you. That’s why, when getting a barbell pad, you need to make sure it’s made from a slip-resistant material of some kind that won’t allow the barbell to roll.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p>One great option is synthetic leather because it also doesn’t absorb sweat and so it won’t start smelling after a few sessions.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338520" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338520"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">FAQs</h2></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338525" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338525"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><b>Should I Use a Barbell Pad for Hip Thrusts?</b></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1700124338527" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1700124338527"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p style="font-size: 20px; font-family: Montserrat, HelveticaNeue, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align: inherit!important; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Yes, you should use a barbell when doing hip thrusts. It will make you feel more comfortable during the movement while also reducing the chances of injury and potential bruises. If you choose not to do so, you risk getting injured or suffering from harsh bruises that will make your sessions more 